    <h4 class="title is-4">Pick up on Broadway</h4>
    <article>

        <p>
            &nbsp;I have four nicely dressed people-two girls and two guys- one of whom is named Raj the owner of the Uber ride. We&rsquo;re just south of Broadway on 3
            <sup>rd</sup> avenue
            <strong>,</strong>and all of my passengers are drunk to varying degrees. Rather than speak, words just fall out of their mouths. It&lsquo;s not late, but already the local wildlife is out and active.
        </p>
        <p>
            Groups of people clump along the sidewalks and outside the bars. A girl sits on the sidewalk crying while two other girls hover close by. Two men shout at one another while people circle around with anticipation. My passengers stare dumbfounded
            as people stream from the Country Music Hall of Fame side street to the other, indifferent to the cars trying to get through. I hear &ldquo;insane&rdquo; and &ldquo;crazy&rdquo; spoken in whispers over and over again. The guy sitting next
            to me takes note of the Sun Caf&eacute;, saying that the same exact caf&eacute; exists in New Orleans. &ldquo;They are trying to turn this place into Bourbon Street,&rdquo; he says.&nbsp;
        </p>
        <p>
            Further up the street and closer to the hotel, the two girls in the party gasp when they see a girl running up the street barefoot. &ldquo;I wouldn&rsquo;t even walk into the Airbnb bathroom without shoes on,&rdquo; says Raj, the owner of
            the ride and the only name I know. We have to stop while the car in front of us stops to let a passenger out so he can throw up on the side of the street. &ldquo;Where are we?&rdquo; one of the girls asks impatiently as the others comment
            excitedly at the sight of a young man screaming at a&nbsp;fire hydrant.
        </p>
        <p>
            &ldquo;Mars,&rdquo; is the answer that comes back from the guy sitting next to me in the passenger seat. I see the young man turn toward away from the fire hydrant towards me, making eye contact. His visage is twisted, his skin sallow as if
            he were dead. Terrified, but conscious of the need to maintain control, I look away. &ldquo;Are we almost at the hotel? I just want to get to bed,&rdquo; one of the girls says and I detect a mood of agreement amongst the group. That is
            except for Raj, the guy who ordered the ride.
        </p>
        <p>&ldquo;I could stay out a little longer actually, &ldquo;he says.</p>
        <p>
            I can almost feel the girl sitting next to him roll her eyes as they exit my car and I close out their trip in the app. I look back at the demon boy yelling at the fire hydrant. The visage is gone, and the guy looks like a normal pitiful drunk
            outside of his head.
        </p>
        <p>
            I&rsquo;m the best driver and the worst driver. That sounds pretentious but it&rsquo;s true. I know I&rsquo;m the best because plenty of my passengers, high on life and whatever other substances they have&nbsp;taken, have told me so. I&rsquo;m
            not afraid to interact with my customers- I can make them laugh and keep them entertained. I&rsquo;m agreeable and nod sympathetically when they tell me stories of the being wronged by so and so. I don&rsquo;t judge when the young woman
            I pick up on a Sunday morning comes to the car wearing a pair of shorts her last night hookup loaned her.
        </p>

        <p>
            But as far as my actual driving is concerned...let&rsquo;s see. I slung two business executives from one side of the car to the other trying to make a last-second turn at full speed. Another guy nearly got whiplash when I made a full stop
            and at almost fifty miles/hour. I&rsquo;ve almost run more than a couple of drivers off of the road who were in my &ldquo;blind spot&rdquo; when I tried to change lanes. I&rsquo;ve been cussed more than once. My wife is convinced that
            I&rsquo;m a terrible driver because I&rsquo;m selfish and self-centered. Maybe she&rsquo;s right. Deep down, driving like a closet maniac offers me a thrill that my unemployed everyman 9 to 5 life doesn&rsquo;t. I&rsquo;ve seen my ratings
            drop from 4.99 to 4.72. The company sends me emails saying that my ratings need to improve or &ldquo;something&rdquo; will happen.
        </p>
        <p>***********************************************************************************</p>
        <p>
            Uber has a parking lot near the airport where drivers looking for airport runs must wait. Most of the drivers sit in their cars with gloomy expressions on their faces. A few get out and stretch their legs as I do one night. While standing
            around watching my breath in the cold January air, I strike up a conversation with another driver named Bill(not his real name). Bill is a long-haired young haired young man who carries himself with a happy go lucky attitude. We exchange
            names, the amount of time we&rsquo;ve been driving among other trivialities. Bill looks at my phone and marvels at the number of badges and good comments that I&rsquo;ve gotten from customers. Bill has no badges and his rating is even
            lower than mine.
        </p>
        <p>
            But it&rsquo;s all good according to Bill. The company emails Bill as well about his ratings, but he pays the emails no mind. He makes 500 to 600 dollars a week driving for the company, doesn&rsquo;t drive on Mondays or Tuesday, and lives
            with his girlfriend in a two bedroom somewhere in Antioch. Bill does alright. He has a tattoo on his wrist with a symbol. Bill rubs the symbol, and lefts his arm up to his mouth and gives the symbol and soft kiss. He mentions that he is
            a fledgling member of a lodge in town. &ldquo;I have to make enough to send up the food chain. I do that and then some, &ldquo; Bill says proudly. I ask about the food chain, but don&rsquo;t get an answer.
        </p>
        <p>Bill has a &ldquo;system&rdquo; for making more money by driving which he shares with a gleam in his eye: strip clubs.</p>
        <p>
            According to Bill, strip clubs will pay drivers for bringing passengers to the club. They pay so much per head, and all the driver has to do is walk in with the passengers to get credit. The clubs pay per head-Bill tells me that he made $100
            on one trip, more than I&rsquo;ve made on quite a few nights. Strip clubs look like the&nbsp;big bucks scheme of ridesharing, and the idea depresses and terrifies me.
        </p>
        <p>*************************************************************************************</p>
        <p>
            I leave for a day of ride sharing. Sixteen hundred is the mortgage amount. That is the number I have to hit by week&rsquo;s end so that my wife and kids don&rsquo;t end up on the street. A slight exaggeration, but true for the most part. I
            know the date will come, but not the money. I think on Bill&rsquo;s hustle and I shudder. Throughout the day as I ferry passengers here and there, I ruminate on my failures as father and husband. A few of the passengers intrude on my silent
            deliberations with banal questions: how&rsquo;s your day going, how busy have you been today, and the crowd favorite: what&rsquo;s the weirdest ride you&rsquo;ve ever had? The last question comes up so much that I have a ready answer that
            I stole from another driver by way of two former passengers of his. The story goes as follows: An old woman had decided to share the rejuvenating experience of having her clitoris pierced with the said driver while he took her to her destination.
            I have no such spectacular story to tell so now a proud old woman with a pierced clit rode in my car as well.
        </p>
        <p>
            Thankfully, most of my riders say nothing to me as I shuttle them to their destination. I enjoy several hours of miserable solitude when a man gets in a car and shares his miraculous near-death experience that he had after getting it by truck
            off 2
            <sup>nd</sup> and Broad. Every day above ground is a good day-how do I know that? I know that because my passenger has says it over and over again.
        </p>
        <p>
            I look at where I&rsquo;m driving and I see what looks to be a tiny figure on the hood of my car. It is three feet high maybe with wrinkled skin and with the same twisted face I saw on the guy screaming at the fire hydrant the other night.
            Is that a gremlin-riding on my hood?!!
        </p>
        <p>I look away and it&rsquo;s gone. I make no mention of it to the man as I carry him to his destination.</p>
        <p>My recruiter calls. There is an opening for a developer in a company called ElderSen. The recruiter tells me that I will be reporting directly to the Director of Application Development.</p>
        <p>***********************************************************************************************************************************************</p>
        <p>
            It is night, and I&rsquo;m downtown with the usual craziness. A man named Krishna enters my car with two associates from a bar in the gulch. They are headed to one of the newer hotels in the gulch that sits squeezed between cranes and the
            steel embryos of yet more hotels. The same craziness and tomfoolery on the streets between 5
            <sup>th</sup> and 1
            <sup>st</sup> of Broadway unfold as always as if drawn forth by instinct or a plague of delirium. These men are older and worldlier and they chuckle at the scenes outside the window.&nbsp;
        </p>
        <p>&ldquo;Do you have anything like this in India, Krishna?&rdquo; one of the men asks in a flat Midwestern accent indicative of anywhere.</p>
        <p>&ldquo;My friend, we have everything in India: sanity, insanity, every extreme of sanctity and sin and everything in between,&rdquo; replied the Krishna.</p>
        <p>&ldquo;I have heard that to be true,&rdquo; the third man piped commenting on time he spent over there.</p>
        <p>
            &ldquo;India is traditionally known by us,&rdquo; Krishna begins in a more somber tone,&rdquo; as
            <em>Bharat</em> or the land of highest consciousness. Our civilization goes back thousands of years as you may know. In the Mahabharata, we have tales of men flying around in machines and waging wars against the Rakshas, or demons as you
            call them. The Rakshas lived in the Underworld. There they drank wine, ate meat, and had sex. &ldquo;
        </p>
        <p>&ldquo;My kind of place,&rdquo; one of the men replies.</p>
        <p>&ldquo;Back in the old days, men would fly around in their flying machines, powered by crystal mercury&hellip;.&rdquo;</p>
        <p>&ldquo;Like ancient aliens,&rdquo; one of the Americans says with a barely concealed smirk. Krishna smiles and continues.</p>
        <p>&ldquo;And fly to the underworld-for vacation,&rdquo; Krishna continues.</p>
        <p>All the men chuckled.</p>
        <p>&ldquo;Yesterday I was in Delhi, and I got on a plane, and where did I fly?&rdquo; Krishna points out the window at a man throwing up on the sidewalk.</p>
        <p>&ldquo;I flew here to the Underworld,&rdquo; Krishna answers waving the air above his head. &ldquo;And somewhere close by,&rdquo; Krishna continued, pointing again to the outside,&rdquo; is its portal.&rdquo;</p>
        <p>******************************************************************************C</p>
    </article>
